London Mess Picheringh & Robbrsen
In answer to yd of 10h surtt. do inclosed send the acctt of goods to ret ded. last, as
alsoo yd curtt. which finding to aggree please to note accodingly. I have not given
you credit for the returned tykes in said acctt. because I had brought itt in this yeares
so itt sall finde itt self. opon a neare examinaion finde to have rec of the
goods sold about ƒ 800- of which the charges must be dedueted whes itt remaines
ƒ500-, for yd ½ ƒ250- there by the loykes returned, will make itt some what more
so that a small remise for £50- on £60- would be wel come, because I see no
great apearence to rembourse mij self soo soone, for all trade comes to nothingh
here & mony is scarey att no rate, I doubt I have not sold abore 2 cloathes
of ours this yeare, part of the rest are in the press, to be reprissed, & I'll endeavour
to cleare that before summer, that with this approaching spring all might be sold
I could wish to be capable to do you some aggreable service
a 28d
Londen mr. Will Scawen
I have before mee yd. of 6 cur, by which I am gladd to understand yd. sase arrwall
as for the £2:10- I charged you for a mistake, may casely well be for upen examinetion
of for mar invoyces, I finde, that I had butt once romales of severall sorts the
silk att 16„6 demy ils att 13, & cotton att 14 - & you sending the last, without any order
madl mee beleave itt was for the great cheap, as jnderd I finde the cotten & demy
silk were cheaper, & should then the silh be dearer by 2„6 a p to be 19 ƒ susteed
of 2„6 less, to be butt 14ƒ, so I finde no great reasen for you to take that un hindscy
& may books beeng ballanced according to the acctts given you, so I can not make that
L
other wise, except I allow something upen yot curtt: with the 2ƒ 6 pence in the farell
of £33„9„6, as also the ƒ5- for yd. share over cast. you complaine of the sale, ondad
had that unfortunate bustynes not haspyned att Bredges, wee might hae made
neare 12 , & the goods have been there thinnold & so mishandled, that they all lost
their, ealander, there by they are worses by 5 p then the last, which cost so much
d
loss, & all the dyed dungarees are still unsold, you knw what they cost, & itt will be the
ntmost if I shall beable to make ƒ6„10- of them, consider there by, that I take the debts
uponmee, & make you good the while, & that upon a serions examination you will not finde
that you have been long out of yd mony, so may considder nee botter, & beleave not
that I am to forward as you write, as if I take all advantoges to my self, I confess I
have charged the sale with ½ for small & badd mony, that every one allowes ma
& I assures you I nather loose by itt, for I do not beleave that any comd sold here
1s payd with worse speta, nay much with hollands mony, because the hollands callicoes
ane so plenty, that wee can gane butt little by y from England, & the veus sell itt
cheapen here of the sale, as att the sale one can have itt, the resting goods are 50
dungareos dyed, 30 salmpores white, of which 2 wrappers altoghether in pecces, on the
conners of the last bale, & 166 salempores dyed which stand us in here ƒ1622 & you
told mee you would leave y mee, as they cost, yett I proffined ƒ 1672.:16, which is 3 p
mone, & in case the goods att the neyl sale are sold cheaper I doubt they will not yeald
in all ƒ1700- for sure callicois must sall cheap in consideration of what awordd of the sort
is arrived, as well in holland as in England: yett to comply whith you, leave miy acctt
ballaned as itt is, for all yd pretenses, & mistakes & resting goods I'll give yd acctt. creditt
for ƒ860- & I'il send you as brave a bale of tykes as everwas sent to England, & as
cheap, butt there is a few 3 seales by, which I'll note so low in prijse that you will
gaine best by them, so exspect yd answer, on order to sell off for our acctt in comp
ts yett shall needs want more goods to putt off these so if they sell for less then forman
dale, please to buy for mee as by the inclosed note you shall finde, for my acctt, as
hence forward I intend to do, & make my trade the less, to finde no blames or contrrdichond
C 28 febr 1681
Londen mr. Willem Scawen
